Employment Opportunities Predictor, place-level

Author

JP Walsh

Published

January 11, 2024

Program for the creation of the Employment Opportunities Predictor at the place-level

ACS Code: Initially written by Tina Chelidze and updated by JP Walsh 2022-2023.

Primary data derived from the IPUMS API.

Based on processes developed by Paul Johnson and Kevin Werner in SAS.

  • Read Data
  • Clean Data
  • Merge Crosswalk
  • Create Income Metric

Housekeeping

Read in packages for use. If you do not have an IPUMS API key you will need to make one via the IPUMS website.

Code 
library(tidyverse)
library(Hmisc)
library(ipumsr)
library(reactable)

options(scipen = 999)

#set_ipums_api_key("Your KEY", save = TRUE)
source(here::here("functions", "API", "extract_ipums.R"))

Read Data

Read in the ACS extracts using the extract_ipums function. Make sure to change the survey list to reflect what years you want to include in the data. Currently we are including three years of 1-year data (2018a, 2021a and 2022a) and two years of 5-year data (2018c and 2021c). 5-year 2022 data will be added pending its release.

Code 
acs <- extract_ipums(
  extract_name = "umf_data_18_22",
  extract_description = "Microdata pull for Mobility Metric Predictors. American Community Survey, years 2018, 2019 and 2022 (1 and 5-year).",
  survey = list("us2018a", "us2021a", "us2022a", "us2018c", "us2021c")
)

Look at the distribution of samples in the data.

Code 
acs %>% 
  count(sample) %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = sample, y = n)) +
  geom_col() +
  theme_minimal() +
  ggtitle("Samples, All Records") +
 geom_text(mapping = aes(label = n), vjust = -1) +    
  scale_y_continuous(expand = expansion(mult = c(0, 0.1))) +
  labs(x = "Samples",
       y = NULL)

Read in the PUMA to place crosswalk file. This file is created by the program generate_puma_place_crosswalks.rmd in the geographic-crosswalks folder.

Code 
puma_place_crosswalk <- read_csv(here::here("geographic-crosswalks", "data", "crosswalk_puma_to_place.csv"))

Crate a version of the crosswalk with just the place-level values of data quality variables for each crosswalk period.

Code 
place_puma <- puma_place_crosswalk %>%
  group_by(crosswalk_period, statefip, place) %>% 
  summarise(geographic_allocation_quality = mean(geographic_allocation_quality)) %>% 
  ungroup()

Clean Data

Missing data is reported in a variety of ways by IPUMS - listed below:

Age: No missing values reported in variable description. Empstat: N/As reported as â0â. Vacancy is reported as â0â.

There is a large share of records missing for empstat. The distribution of age looks reasonable (no bunching or extreme outliers). Note there are no vacancy results by default of the structure of census data read in.

Code 
acs %>% 
  count(empstat) %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = factor(empstat), y = n)) +
  geom_col() +
  theme_minimal() +
  ggtitle("Empstat, All Records") +
 geom_text(mapping = aes(label = n), vjust = -1) +    
  scale_y_continuous(expand = expansion(mult = c(0, 0.1))) +
  labs(x = "Employment Status",
       y = NULL)

Code 
acs %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = age)) +

  theme_minimal() +
  ggtitle("Age Variable Results") +
  ylab("Density")

acs %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = vacancy)) +
  geom_density(color = "blue", fill = alpha("blue", 0.3)) +
  theme_minimal() +
  ggtitle("Vacancy Variable Results") +

Turn the missing/ânot in universeâ value from the empstat variable into NAs.

Code 
acs_clean <- acs %>%
  mutate(empstat = ifelse(empstat == 0, NA_integer_,
                          empstat)
  )

Look at distribution of empstat after adjustment. There should be no more records with the value â0â.

Create race variable

Evaluate the values in the RACE and HISPAN variables.

  • IPUMS documented values for RACE:
    • 1 White
    • 2 Black/African American/Negro
    • 3 American Indian or Alaska Native
    • 4 Chinese
    • 5 Japanese
    • 6 Other Asian or Pacific Islander
    • 7 Other race
    • 8 Two major races
    • 9 Three or more major races
  • IPUMS documented values for HISPAN:
    • 0 Not Hispanic
    • 1 Mexican
    • 2 Puerto Rican
    • 3 Cuban
    • 4 Other
    • 9 Not Reported

Check that group quarters fall only into household categories.

Code 
acs_clean %>% 
  count(race) %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = race, y = n)) +
  geom_col() +
  theme_minimal() +

 geom_text(mapping = aes(label = n), vjust = -1) +

 geom_text(mapping = aes(label = n), vjust = -1) +

  labs(x = "Hispan",

Create the race/ethnicity variable. For other race/ethnicity categories not coded as Hispanic, Hispan must be equal to âNot Hispanicâ.

Rename the values from number category to race label: +Race is 2 and Hispan is 0 = âBlack, Non-Hispanicâ +Hispan is >=1 and <=4 = âHispanicâ +Race is >=3 and <=9 and Hispan is 0 = âOther Races and Ethnicitiesâ +Race is 4 and Hispan is 0 = âWhite, Non-Hispanicâ

Code 
acs_clean <- acs_clean %>%
  mutate(subgroup = case_when((hispan == "Not Hispanic" & race == "White") ~ "White, Non-Hispanic",
                              (hispan == "Not Hispanic" & race == "Black/African American") ~ "Black, Non-Hispanic",
                              (hispan == "Not Hispanic" & !race %in% c("Black/African American", "White")) ~ "Other Races and Ethnicities",
                               hispan != "Not Hispanic" ~ "Hispanic"
  ))

Look at subgroup distribution.

Code

       y = NULL)

Create a variable in the ACS data indicating whether the survey is pre or post-2022. This will be used to join on the correct crosswalk information.

Code 
acs_clean <- acs_clean %>%

  filter(!is.na(afact))

Code 
acs_clean <- acs_clean %>% 
  filter(afact > 0)

Adjust the person weight to account for PUMA-to-place mapping (those where unique_types do not equal 1).

Code 
acs_clean <- acs_clean %>%
  mutate(perwt = perwt*afact
  )

Create employment metric

Create the employment metric.

Objective: get the percent of individuals between the ages 25 and 54 that are employed from the EMPSTAT variable.

Aggregation should be weighted by PERWT (this is a person level statistic).

First, isolate the dataset to 25-54 year-olds.

Code 
microdata_emp_age <- acs_clean %>% 
  filter(age >= 25 & age <= 54)

Check how many records, if any, have NA reported for empstat after filtering.

Code 
microdata_emp_age %>%
  filter(is.na(empstat)) %>% 
  group_by(pernum) %>% 
  count()
# A tibble: 0 x 2
# Groups:   pernum [0]
# i 2 variables: pernum <dbl>, n <int>

Confirm there are no vacant properties included in the data.

Code 
microdata_emp_age %>%
  filter(is.na(vacancy)) %>% 
  group_by(pernum) %>% 
  count()
# A tibble: 0 x 2
# Groups:   pernum [0]
# i 2 variables: pernum <dbl>, n <int>

Create a binary variable to distinguish between 1 and 5 year ACS datasets. 5-year samples include the term â5-yearâ.

Code 
microdata_emp_age <- microdata_emp_age %>%
  mutate(sample_structure = ifelse(str_detect(sample, "5-year"), "5year", "1year"))

Check national employment ratio.

Code 
metrics_employment <- microdata_emp_age %>%
  filter(sample_structure == "1year") %>% 
  group_by(year) %>%
  summarise(
    num_in_emp_age = sum(perwt),
    num_employed = sum((empstat == 1) * perwt),
    count = n()
  ) %>% 
  ungroup()

Compute the ratio (share employed) for 2018, 2021 and 2022 nationally.

Code 
metrics_employment %>%
  mutate(share_employed = num_employed/num_in_emp_age) %>% 
  reactable()

All

Create share employed for all individuals at the place-level (1-year data).

Code 
metrics_employment_all <- microdata_emp_age %>%
  filter(sample_structure == "1year") %>% 
  group_by(year, crosswalk_period, statefip, place) %>%
  summarise(
    num_in_emp_age = sum(perwt),
    num_employed = sum((empstat == 1) * perwt),
    count = n(),
    effective_sample = sum(afact)
  ) %>% 
  ungroup()

Compute the ratio (share employed).

Code 
metrics_employment_all <- metrics_employment_all %>%
  mutate(share_employed = num_employed/num_in_emp_age)

Sort by year, state and place.

Code 
metrics_employment_all <- metrics_employment_all %>%
  arrange(year, statefip, place)

Create an indicator for data quality and suppression

Merge the data quality flags and create the final data quality metric based on both size and geographic allocation.

Code 
metrics_employment_all <- left_join(metrics_employment_all, place_puma, by=c("crosswalk_period", "statefip","place"))

Tabulate effective sample counts for each place, defined as the sum of the afact for all records in that place. Look at the distribution of places by potential cutoffs (30, 100, 300). This is to measure data quality for each place based on the number of records reported. In the 1-year data for all there are no cases of a place with less than 100 observations for 2018, 2021 and 2022.

Code 
metrics_employment_all %>%
  mutate(
    effective_sample_cutoffs = case_when(
      effective_sample < 30 ~ "Less than 30",
      effective_sample >= 30 &
        effective_sample <= 100 ~ "Over 30 but 100 or less",
      effective_sample > 100 &
        effective_sample <= 300 ~ "Over 100 but 300 or less",
      TRUE ~ "Greater than 300"
    ),
    effective_sample_cutoffs = factor(
      effective_sample_cutoffs,
      levels = c(
        "Less than 30",
        "Over 30 but 100 or less",
        "Over 100 but 300 or less",
        "Greater than 300"
      )
    )
  ) %>%
  group_by(year, effective_sample_cutoffs) %>%
  count() %>%
  mutate(supression_share = n / 485) %>%
  reactable()

Generate the quality variable for each place.

Code 
metrics_employment_all <- metrics_employment_all %>% 
  mutate(effective_sample_flag = ifelse(effective_sample < 100, 1, 0),
         share_employed_quality = case_when(effective_sample_flag==0 & geographic_allocation_quality==1 ~ 1,
                                     effective_sample_flag==0 & geographic_allocation_quality==2 ~ 2,
                                     effective_sample_flag==0 & geographic_allocation_quality==3 ~ 3,
                                     effective_sample_flag==1 ~ 3)
  )

We do not want to show values that are calculated from less than 30 samples in the data. These points will be suppressed and shown as missing or NA. Suppress the results for values generated from less than 30 samples.

Code 
metrics_employment_all <- metrics_employment_all %>% 
  mutate_at(c("share_employed"), ~if_else(effective_sample < 30, NA_integer_, .))

Keep only relevant variables.

Code 
metrics_employment_all <- metrics_employment_all %>%
  select(year,
         statefip,
         place,
         share_employed,
         share_employed_quality)

Subgroup

Create share employed by race/ethnicity at the place-level (5-year data).

Code 
metrics_employment_subgroup <- microdata_emp_age %>%
  filter(sample_structure == "5year") %>% 
  group_by(year, crosswalk_period, statefip, place, subgroup) %>%
  summarise(
    num_in_emp_age = sum(perwt),
    num_employed = sum((empstat == 1) * perwt),
    count = n(),
    effective_sample = sum(afact)
  )%>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  mutate(subgroup_type = "race-ethnicity")

Compute the ratio (share employed).

Code 
metrics_employment_subgroup <- metrics_employment_subgroup %>%
  mutate(share_employed = num_employed/num_in_emp_age)

Create the share employed measure for all values in the 5-year data. This will be merged onto the subgroup data.

Code 
metrics_employment_subgroup_all <- microdata_emp_age %>%
  filter(sample_structure == "5year") %>% 
  group_by(year, crosswalk_period, statefip, place) %>%
  summarise(
    num_in_emp_age = sum(perwt),
    num_employed = sum((empstat == 1) * perwt),
    count = n(),
    effective_sample = sum(afact)
  )%>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  mutate(subgroup_type = "all",
         subgroup = "All")

metrics_employment_subgroup_all <- metrics_employment_subgroup_all %>%
  mutate(share_employed = num_employed/num_in_emp_age)

Append the âAllâ version of the 5-year data.

Code 
metrics_employment_sub <- bind_rows(metrics_employment_subgroup, metrics_employment_subgroup_all)
